   <topic id="Configuring_GPIO" ditaarch:DITAArchVersion="1.2" domains="(topic hi-d)                             (topic ut-d)                             (topic indexing-d)                            (topic hazard-d)                            (topic abbrev-d)                            (topic pr-d)                             (topic sw-d)                            (topic ui-d)                            (topic struct-d)                            (topic firmware-d)                            (topic pmcrevhis-d)   " class="- topic/topic " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="topic:3;72:26">
      <title class="- topic/title " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="title:4;75:29">GPIO Adapters</title>
      <body class="- topic/body " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="body:3;78:27">
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="p:4;81:24">A GPIO expander is a TWI device used to expand the number of GPIO pins available to the device. When using GPIO expanders that use the same TWI address, TWI expanders can be used to increase the number of TWI buses available. The Configuration File defines this connection relationship for each GPIO adapter.</p>
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="p:5;84:24">If the GPIO expander is connected to an on-chip TWI port, you must set the connected TWI port and TWI address of the GPIO expander. If the GPIO expander is connected to a TWI expander, you must set the TWI expander instance index for this TWI expander and TWI address of the GPIO expander. The GPIO expander’s interrupt signal needs to be routed either to the on-chip GPIO pin directly or to the board FPGA, which will then route the signal to the on-chip GPIO pin. In both cases, for each GPIO adapter users must set the Associated on-chip Input Interrupt GPIO Pin for this on-chip GPIO pin number. When configuring the GPIO expander interrupt, it is recommended to trigger on a falling edge instead of a level change on most GPIO Expanders; However, for the MAX7311/PCA9555 compatible GPIO Expander, The interrupt type only support "4 – Level Changed".</p>
         <note class="- topic/note " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="note:2;87:30">
            <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="p:6;90:27">The maximum number of GPIO Adapters supported in Switchtec is <b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="b:5;92:30">32</b>
            </p>
         </note>
      </body>
   </topic>
   <topic id="Configuring_GPIO-2" ditaarch:DITAArchVersion="1.2" domains="(topic hi-d)                             (topic ut-d)                             (topic indexing-d)                            (topic hazard-d)                            (topic abbrev-d)                            (topic pr-d)                             (topic sw-d)                            (topic ui-d)                            (topic struct-d)                            (topic firmware-d)                            (topic pmcrevhis-d)   " class="- topic/topic " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="topic:4;102:26">
      <title class="- topic/title " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="title:5;105:29">SGPIO Adapters</title>
      <body class="- topic/body " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="body:4;108:27">
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="p:7;111:24">A SGPIO adapter is a SGPIO bus, each bit in SDOUT stream represents a virtual GPIO output pin, and each bit in SDIN stream represents a virtual GPIO input pin. Each input pin can be configured as interrupt and the interrupt type only support "4 – Level Changed". The SGPIO hardware supports up to 256 pins, the range of the number of pins is 0 to 255, where number 0 represents 256 pins.</p>
      </body>
   </topic>
   <topic id="Configuring_GPIO-3" ditaarch:DITAArchVersion="1.2" domains="(topic hi-d)                             (topic ut-d)                             (topic indexing-d)                            (topic hazard-d)                            (topic abbrev-d)                            (topic pr-d)                             (topic sw-d)                            (topic ui-d)                            (topic struct-d)                            (topic firmware-d)                            (topic pmcrevhis-d)   " class="- topic/topic " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="topic:5;119:26">
      <title class="- topic/title " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="title:6;122:29">Virtual GPIO Adapters</title>
      <body class="- topic/body " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="body:5;125:27">
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="p:8;128:24">A virtual GPIO adapter is a software driven GPIO adapter. The back end of it does not talk to physical HW. Instead, FW stores the state of the signal. When this adapter is used to write a value to a virtual GPIO, the internal state of the pin is updated and a FW callback is triggered. If the virtual GPIO state is read, the last written value will be returned. The interrupt type only support "4 – Level Changed".</p>
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="p:9;131:24">Virtual GPIOs can be used to control pins which would normally be physical in nature. This can be very useful in cases where a physical pin may not be available. The PERSTB between host to switch could be one such use case where a physical pin is not available in the cabling between the host and switch. In this case, a virtual GPIO can be configured to control PERST_IN in <xref href="../../../../Saratoga/Saratoga_Configuration/Topic/Partition_Setting_Block_1iibnybo8d.xml" class="- topic/xref " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="xref:1;134:34" type="topic"><?ditaot gentext?>Partition Setting Block</xref>. The MRPC command <i class="+ topic/ph hi-d/i " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="i:1;136:27">gpio_pin_write</i> can then be used over MRPC to provide an in-band mechanism to toggle PERST_IN to the switch which would provide a virtual PERST_IN signal to the switch independent of the host physical pin (which is unconnected). See <xref href="../../../../Saratoga/Saratoga_Configuration/Topic/MRPC_02_GPIO.xml" class="- topic/xref " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="xref:2;139:34" type="topic"><?ditaot gentext?>GPIO Command</xref> for more details.</p>
         <fig class="- topic/fig " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="fig:2;142:28">
            <title class="- topic/title " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="title:7;145:35">GPIO Adapter Setting</title>
            <image href="../../../../Saratoga/Saratoga_Configuration/Graphics/gpio_adapter.png" placement="inline" width="4in" class="- topic/image " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="image:2;151:36"/>
         </fig>
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="p:10;155:25">More details on configuring GPIO can also be found in <xref href="../../../../Saratoga/Saratoga_Configuration/Topic/GPIO_Adapter_Setting_Block_49ibnybo8g.xml" class="- topic/xref " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\gpio\trident_gpio_overview.xml" xtrc="xref:3;158:34" type="topic"><?ditaot gentext?>GPIO Adapter Setting Block</xref>.</p>
      </body>
